Spectroscopic characterization of CDs (blue), EB (red) & CDs mixed with EB (CDs/EB Striped yellow) A) Fluorescence spectra recorded at λex ∼ 300 nm & B) UV–Vis spectra. The concentration here is of CDs - 2.8 μg/ml & of EB - 96 μM. C) Fluorescence spectra & D) UV–Vis spectra of CDs-Probe & CDs/Probe mixed with EB. Fluorescence spectra were recorded at λex ∼350 nm. E) Fluorescence spectra & F) UV–Vis spectra of CDs-Probe/EB & CDs/Probe/EB in presence of TS. G) Lifetime decay profile of CDs, CDs/Probe, CDs/Probe/EB, CDs/Probe/EB/TS. I) Lifetime decay profile of CDs, CDs-Probe, CDs-Probe/EB, CDs-Probe/EB/TS. H
                     ) and J
                     ) Zoomed version of decay profile near IRF region. The concentration of CDs in C), D), E) and F) is 0.078 μg/ml and of EB is ∼95 μM. The same sample is used as above but with a 4 time less dilution for the lifetime decay profile. (For interpretation of the references to color in this figure legend, the reader is referred to the Web version of this article.)

ce:section.ce:para:
The concentration-dependent analytical performance of Non-Func and Func sensors was investigated using short TS (for the sequence see Table 2
                        ), similar to the conserved region of the enteroviral RNA. Both sensors were screened against target viral sequences from 0.5 nM to 5 μM. For the Non-Func sensor, comprised of free CDs (0.45 mg/mL), single-stranded probe (3.3 μM), and EB (30 μM), increasing concentrations of TS led to a gradual increase in EB's PL emission intensity, while CD's intensity remained almost the same showing only slight variations. As shown in Fig. 5
                        D and E, A linear relationship was observed from 100 nM to 3 μM, with a regression equation, y = 2.67 × 10−4 (nM−1) ∗x + 0.08 and an R2 value of 0.984 (Fig. 5F). The LOD of Non-Func sensor was 88.7 nM, with error bars indicating compromised reliability and repeatability. LOD was calculated by averaging 10 blank samples followed by the determination of standard deviation via error propagation of standard deviation of the measurements. The error bars in the figures are obtained in a similar manner. The standard deviation and slope of the linear regression plot were used in equation (2) for LOD calculations. The calculations to estimate LOD have been explained in SI section S11-D. Parameters for individual components of the Non-Func sensor such as CDs, CDs/Probe and CDs/Probe/EB were also investigated with different concentrations of TS and are detailed in SI, sections S6 (Fig. S11), S7 (Fig. S12), and S8 (Fig. S13), respectively.
